## Notes

Please note that for any secondary volume, you need to set the **licence_type** property to **UNKNOWN**

⚠️ **Note:** Important for deleting an <span pulumi-lang-nodejs="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-dotnet="`Firewall`" pulumi-lang-go="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-python="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-yaml="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-java="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-hcl="`firewall`">`firewall`</span> rule from within a list of inline resources defined on the same nic. There is one limitation to removing one firewall rule
from the middle of the list of <span pulumi-lang-nodejs="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-dotnet="`Firewall`" pulumi-lang-go="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-python="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-yaml="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-java="`firewall`" pulumi-lang-hcl="`firewall`">`firewall`</span> rules. Terraform will actually modify the existing rules and delete the last one.
More details here. There is a workaround described in the issue 
that involves moving the resources in the list prior to deletion.
`terraform state mv <resource-name>.<resource-id>[<i>] <resource-name>.<resource-id>[<j>]`

## Import

Resource VCPU Server can be imported using the `resource id` and the `datacenter id`, for example, passing only resource id and datacenter id means that the first nic found linked to the server will be attached to it.

```sh
terraform import ionoscloud_vcpu_server.myserver datacenter uuid/server uuid
```
Optionally, you can pass <span pulumi-lang-nodejs="`primaryNic`" pulumi-lang-dotnet="`PrimaryNic`" pulumi-lang-go="`primaryNic`" pulumi-lang-python="`primary_nic`" pulumi-lang-yaml="`primaryNic`" pulumi-lang-java="`primaryNic`" pulumi-lang-hcl="`primary_nic`">`primaryNic`</span> and <span pulumi-lang-nodejs="`firewallruleId`" pulumi-lang-dotnet="`FirewallruleId`" pulumi-lang-go="`firewallruleId`" pulumi-lang-python="`firewallrule_id`" pulumi-lang-yaml="`firewallruleId`" pulumi-lang-java="`firewallruleId`" pulumi-lang-hcl="`firewallrule_id`">`firewallruleId`</span> so terraform will know to import also the first nic and firewall rule (if it exists on the server):
```sh
terraform import ionoscloud_vcpu_server.myserver datacenter uuid/server uuid/primary nic id/firewall rule id
```

